textAnnotations.description:
638
Outcrop characterization of an early Miocene slope fan system,
Chelif Basin, Algeria
Massive siltstones occupied 4% of the lithologies in the section. They overlaid ripple
and climbing-ripple laminate sets or, less commonly, planar-laminated sandstone and
laminated siltstones (Gao et al., 2009). In addition, many channel bases were lined
with massive siltstone. An intense degree of bioturbation was common throughout the
siltstone (Fig. 311I).
2.4. Marl
Marl was the main component in the slope fan multisystem. It occupied more than
60% of the total thickness of strata examined in the outcrop. In sequence stratigraphy,
marl is regarded as the outcome of a flooding surface. These units are interpreted as
low-energy and low-density deposits (Fig. 31V) (Jiang, 2003).
Picture I shows conglomerate at the bottom of the slope fan. Picture II shows massive
sandstone that includes plenty of prominent vertical Scolicia burrows in the middle of
the slope fan. Picture III shows siltstone lithofacies above the basal conglomerate of the
slope fan. Picture IV shows dark gray marl that indicates very low rates of sedimentation
and flooding surfaces at the top of the slope fan.
3. SEQUENCE INTERPRETATION
3.1. Sequence frame
Based on outcrop, the slope fan belonged to lowstand system tract of the Lower
Miocene (early Miocene) sequence. The location of slope fan was at the edge of the
basin where the highstand system tract was eroded too thin to be detected. Meanwhile
the transgression system tract only developed on slope fan system (Fig. 4), beginning
with thick and pure marlstone (Bilal and Stephen, 2008). The slope fan system was the
main part of the lowstand system tract which was characterized as the eustatic changing
from a slow decrease to an increase.
At outcrop section A1, the entire slope fan system was found. It comprised six
cycles of the lowstand system tract, each between 20 and 50 m thick. These cycles can
be divided into two parasequence groups (S1 and S2). The lower one (S1) is
progradational and included two cycles, and the upper (S2) was retrogradational and
included four cycles (Fig. 5). Each cycle was bounded by prominent planar contacts
and displayed an internal, upward thinning sandstone beds in upper groups. The upper
part of each cycle consisted of siltstone with thin interbedded marl. The lower group
had a conglomerate bed at the bottom of the cycle that showed onlap over the
unconformity surface. Though the lower group was progradational, it was interpreted
as an episodic pulse of sediment in which the supply of sediment waned through time
(He et al., 2007). Commonly, the entire fan system was clearly found in both outcrop
and seismic reflection profile, because of the typical onlap and opposing dip angles of
some interbeds. These stacked units were represented as a series of thin, well-stratified
sedimentary packages in seismic profiles. The mounded morphology with downlap,
shown in seismic reflection profiles, at the front edge of the slope fan is interpreted to
represent a cross section of individual slope fan lobe. The angular discordance among
the packages suggests that they represent discrete slope fan lobes that coalesce with
preceding lobes.
